Sample 6:  Demonstrates item deletion with conflict

 

 

Starting State:  v6.xml

 

 

Endpoint 1 updates:

  • Delete item with id=“ep2.100”

 

Endpoint1 output file: ep1_v6a.xml

 

 

Endpoint 2 updates:

  • Delete item with id=“ep2.100”

 

Endpoint2 output file: ep2_v6a.xml

 

 

Merged Result: v7.xml

 

 

Notable Observations:

  • Note that deleted item's “tombstone” is retained (including item change history)
  • The deleted attribute is set to true for the item’s sx:sync element
  • By the rules of the sync algorithm, this is a conflicting operation even though two delete operations on the same item are not semantically a conflict.
  • The loser’s item element was added to the sx:conflicts element

 

 

<item>

<sx:sync id="ep2.100" updates="2" deleted="true" noconflicts="false">

<sx:history sequence="2" when="2007-01-19T00:14:40Z" by="EP2" />

<sx:history sequence="1" when="2007-01-19T00:14:37Z" by="EP2" />

<sx:conflicts>

<item>

<sx:sync id="ep2.100" updates="2" deleted="true" noconflicts="false">

<sx:history sequence="2" when="2007-01-19T00:14:40Z" by="EP1">

<sx:history sequence="1" when="2007-01-19T00:14:37Z" by="EP2">

</sx:sync>

<title>Return books to library</title>

<description>2 books in total</description>

</item>

</sx:conflicts>

</sx:sync>

<title>Return books to library</title>

<description>2 books in total</description>

</item>
